## Steps to Reproduce

Open that code in Android Studio

```dart
    Container(
      child: Column(
        children: [
          Row(
            children: [Text("")],
          ),
          Row(
            children: [Text("")],
          ),
          Row(
            children: [Text("")],
          ),
        ],
      ),
    );

```

You can NOT see collapse / expand buttons at the left.
Then add "new" words everywhere.
You can DO see  collapse / expand buttons at the left.

```dart
    new Container(
      child: new Column(
        children: [
          new Row(
            children: [Text("")],
          ),
          new Row(
            children: [Text("")],
          ),
          new Row(
            children: [Text("")],
          ),
        ],
      ),
    );
```

## Expected behavior

See collapse / expand buttons in both the cases (with and without "new" words)

comment_data.body:
Thanks for the report!

@jwren, I believe the folding here is done by IntelliJ (and not the analysis server). Do you see a way to add support for optional new + const (w/o also showing folding section for every method call)?

No, the Dart PSI elements only know that they are constructors because of the new and const keywords.  To preserve the functionality here, we'd probably choose to fold on methods that start with a capitalized letter, which is not ideal, but would probably be sufficient.

What is worse is that gathering up all the method invocations takes time, for some Dart developers with larger files, we'd be adding more cost (in the form of lag), than value (folding of constructor invocations.)

We definitely shouldn't leave it as is, if we don't fold `Foo(...);`, we shouldn't be folding `new Foo(...);`.

I don't have any strong opinion here either way, but am happy to do this task.
Note that the analysis server supports code folding and _does_ know whether the thing being invoked is a constructor.
Please fix this ASAP, this code folding feature for DART is a must have for me...
Closing.  This should be fixed in the 2019.1 release of the Dart Plugin.

How to install the 2019.1 release of the Dart Plugin? 
@jwren It says that this is not compatible . I used android studio 3.3

This feature was patched into the 182.5215 (2018.2.5 -- aka IntelliJ version used by Android Studio 3.3) a few hours ago, and released, https://plugins.jetbrains.com/plugin/6351-dart by @alexander-doroshko 

Updating to the latest Dart Plugin (Setting > Plugins > Dart) should give you this feature.
